# 11. Source IDs

Every source must have a canonical source ID.

## 11.1 Pattern

```text
SRC-<FAMILY>-<NNN>
```

## 11.2 Allowed family codes

* `MUS` = museum_conservation
* `PIG` = pigment_reference
* `MFR` = manufacturer
* `COL` = color_theory
* `HIS` = historical_practice
* `SCI` = scientific_paper

## 11.3 Examples

* `SRC-MUS-001`
* `SRC-PIG-014`
* `SRC-MFR-032`
* `SRC-COL-005`

## 11.4 Rule

Source IDs are permanent once assigned.

Do not recycle IDs if a source is rejected or superseded.

---

# 12. Chunk IDs

Every chunk must have a canonical chunk ID.

## 12.1 Pattern

```text
CHK-<SOURCE_ID>-<NNN>
```

## 12.2 Examples

* `CHK-SRC-MUS-001-001`
* `CHK-SRC-MFR-004-002`

## 12.3 Rule

Chunk numbering should be sequential within the source.

If rechunking occurs, either:

* regenerate the full chunk set and version the chunk artifacts
  or
* preserve old chunk metadata in history and promote the new chunk set clearly

Do not silently reuse old chunk IDs for semantically different chunk boundaries.

---

# 13. Raw Source Files

These live in `data/raw/...`

## 13.1 Pattern

```text
<SOURCE_ID>_<short_source_stem>.<ext>
```

## 13.2 Examples

* `SRC-MUS-001_smalt_degradation.pdf`
* `SRC-MFR-004_williamsburg_zinc_white.html`
* `SRC-COL-001_munsell_value.html`

## 13.3 Source stem rules

The short source stem should be:

* lowercase
* concise
* descriptive
* stable

Avoid overlong stems.

Good:

* `smalt_degradation`
* `zinc_white`
* `munsell_value`

Bad:

* `this_is_the_full_title_of_the_document_with_extra_words`

## 13.4 Snapshot rule for time-sensitive sources

For product pages and changing web sources, use:

```text
<SOURCE_ID>_<short_source_stem>_<YYYY-MM-DD>.<ext>
```

Example:

* `SRC-MFR-004_williamsburg_zinc_white_2026-03-08.html`

Use this when multiple captures of the same source will coexist.

---

# 14. Clean / Normalized Files

These live in `data/clean/...`

## 14.1 Markdown normalization

```text
<SOURCE_ID>_<short_source_stem>.md
```

Example:

* `SRC-MUS-001_smalt_degradation.md`

## 14.2 Extracted tables

Use:

```text
<SOURCE_ID>_<short_source_stem>_tables.json
```

or

```text
<SOURCE_ID>_<short_source_stem>_table_<NN>.csv
```

Examples:

* `SRC-MUS-001_smalt_degradation_tables.json`
* `SRC-MFR-004_williamsburg_zinc_white_table_01.csv`

## 14.3 Metadata sidecar

Use:

```text
<SOURCE_ID>.json
```

Example:

* `SRC-MUS-001.json`

Rule:
Source metadata should not depend on the text stem. The ID is the stable identity.

